1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
This is Maya Fishler, and I'm in the home of Jean Starker Roth.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Today is October 31st, 2007, and Jean and I are going to be talking about the years

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:24,000
when she was raising a family here in Corvallis, her life with Kermit, and that section of her life.

4
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:32,000
And you did a great job in your interview with Wade, telling about how you met Kermit.

5
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:40,000
So I don't want to make you repeat that story, but it is a wonderful story about how you two came together.

6
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,000
But I'd like to know a little bit more.

7
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:52,000
The questions that he didn't ask you are the kinds of questions that a woman has a tendency more to ask in terms of what it was about him that attracted you.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,000
How you knew he was the right man for you at the very early days there.

9
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Well, I had been dating a lot of boys out at the, not only at Campadier, but also in Park in Astoria, at the USO, and officers clubs up there.

10
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:27,000
And I don't know when I met Kermit, we just hit it off and the first date that we had after the original date at the fraternity house.

11
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:34,000
We just talked and talked and talked and everything was just, you know, we agreed on a lot of things.

12
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:36,000
He was an easy person to spend time with.

13
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Yes, that's right.

14
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:44,000
And so I think that that, and of course he was tall and he was good looking.

15
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Lots of people said that he looked just like Gary Cooper.

16
00:01:48,000 --> 00:02:02,000
In fact, when I obtained his picture to put in my apartment in Astoria, when I had people come they'd say, why do you have Gary Cooper's picture in you?

17
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:04,000
Wow, that's quite a statement.

18
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:17,000
And also, after we were married, sometimes we'd go to a gas station and the gas station boys would come up and then after they put the gas in several times this happened.

19
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:24,000
They would knock on my door and they'd say, did anybody ever tell you your husband looks like Gary Cooper?

20
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Well, that's quite a compliment.

21
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:31,000
So you dated for about a year before you got married?

22
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:44,000
We met in September because that was State Fair and P.I., which was Pacific International.

23
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:49,000
That was a big thing with extension.

24
00:02:49,000 --> 00:03:02,000
Then Thanksgiving he planted his paternity pin and a Christmas we announced our engagement and we were married in June.

25
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:04,000
That's a pretty quick turnaround.

26
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,000
So it was September that you met him.

27
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Yes.

28
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:11,000
Ha, well, you must have been pretty sure then that he was the right man.

29
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Yes, that's right.

30
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:15,000
There was never any doubt in my mind.

31
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:23,000
Well, what were some of the things that you did together in that those first six months that helped to secure your relationship?

32
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Well, I think that we spent a lot of time with our families and I think that was very educational because from then on, from the time we met he would come to Astoria.

33
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:50,000
I had an apartment in a big old, what do I want to say?

34
00:03:50,000 --> 00:04:02,000
It was a very old, old house and the people that I lived with had two little girls.

35
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:15,000
And I think they wanted me to live there because I could occasionally babysit if they wanted to go to a late movie they knew I was home and could watch the girls.

36
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,000
But we stopped.

37
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:21,000
I lost my drink.

38
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
You spent a time with your family.

39
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Yes, well, he would come up and they offered for him to stay in their bedroom, a bedroom adjoining my unit.

40
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:41,000
And then the next weekend we'd go to his mother's house and can be with me there.

41
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:48,000
And then the next weekend we'd come down to Carvalis and he was at the fraternity and I was with my parents.

42
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:49,000
I see.

43
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:52,000
You know, in those days you didn't live together before you married.

44
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Absolutely not.

45
00:04:53,000 --> 00:05:01,000
But we were at one of our, one of those three places every weekend from that time on.

46
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Yeah.

47
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
So your parents got to know him pretty quickly.

48
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,000
Yes, yes.

49
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:06,000
How did they like him?

50
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:08,000
They thought he was fine.

51
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
They liked him from the start, huh?

52
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
Never, never really discussed it.

53
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:19,000
But I remember very distinctly saying, now if you have any, I'm going to marry this man.

54
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:23,000
If you got any objections, tell me now.

55
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,000
Well, good.

56
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:28,000
I'm like you had gotten pretty bold over the years.

57
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:32,000
You've come a long way from those early days.

58
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:35,000
So he was still going to school at that time.

59
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
Because he had started school.

60
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:41,000
And do you want me to tell you a little bit about his background?

61
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:42,000
Absolutely.

62
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:43,000
Okay.

63
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:50,000
Well, Carvalis was raised in Monmouth because his father was superintendent of schools there.

64
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:57,000
And I guess that Carvalis played Monmouth in football and he played football.

65
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,000
But I didn't know a man.

66
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:10,000
And then his father wanted to get his doctorate degree.

67
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,000
So Carvalis joined the 3C.

68
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Well, he went to school, I think, one term.

69
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:23,000
And then his dad didn't have enough money to go and get a doctorate.

70
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:28,000
So Carvalis joined the 3C's and he sent his money home from that.

71
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
So his dad could get his doctorate.

72
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,000
And then...

73
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:35,000
That was right after high school?

74
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:36,000
Yes.

75
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:44,000
Then his father did get his doctorate.

76
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:48,000
But it was during the war by then.

77
00:06:48,000 --> 00:07:07,000
And he was asked to go to Portland to teach welders how to not only weld.

78
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,000
No, that's wrong.

79
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:16,000
He was asked to teach welders how to teach welders.

80
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,000
No, interesting.

81
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:23,000
Because a lot of them knew how to weld, but they couldn't teach people how to weld.

82
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:29,000
So he was employed to do that, to teach.

83
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:38,000
And then Carvalis went in the service and his father died while he was overseas.

84
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:42,000
So the Red Cross flew him home.

85
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:45,000
I didn't know him at this point in life.

86
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:52,000
And then his mother had always taught at school.

87
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:57,000
And she moved to Canby and bought a house.

88
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:01,000
And it was a four or five bedroom house.

89
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:06,000
And she took in teachers because she was so lonely.

90
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:12,000
So that developed when we were married.

91
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:18,000
And then she died when we had to get a house.

92
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:24,000
We had to buy a house that fit our furniture because she had all these beds and mattresses.

93
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
Oh, did you inherit it?

94
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,000
Yes.

95
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
We inherited all her furniture.

96
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Oh, right.

97
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
You could have started a rooming house yourself.

98
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:33,000
That's right.

99
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:41,000
But the bedding and all of that was so good to give away.

100
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:43,000
So we tried to keep it.

101
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:46,000
And of course eventually we used it with all our cans.

102
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
That's a good thing.

103
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:53,000
So where was Kermit in the war?

104
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:02,000
He was Tinian, which is a little island about a mile by a mile and a half.

105
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:07,000
Very close to...

106
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:13,000
Oh, I'll have to think about that.

107
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:15,000
I'll have to get you the name of that.

108
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:18,000
But you'd know it if you heard it.

109
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
It was very much in the news.

110
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
But it was a small island.

111
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
But there were jabs on it.

112
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:38,000
And they never knew when they were going to run into somebody who was hiding in that island.

113
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:50,000
But that was when he learned to scuba dive because he was a mechanic repairing airplanes that had been shot down.

114
00:09:50,000 --> 00:10:04,000
And so he took the plexiglass and made a mask and took the rubber off the tires and it had blown.

115
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:08,000
And made the back of the mask.

116
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:17,000
And he made quite a little money during that period because he would dive for shells.

117
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:24,000
And I don't know how many shoe boxes of shells when we were married.

118
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:27,000
He brought those with him.

119
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:31,000
So he took advantage of being in a tropical location?

120
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:32,000
Yes, he did.

121
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:41,000
And he always blessed the government for sending him to a warm climate because he said that he never would have survived in Europe with a cold.

122
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:44,000
He did like to be cold.

123
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,000
So he was with the Air Force.

124
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:49,000
But he didn't fly. He was always a mechanic.

125
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:51,000
Well, he intended to fly.

126
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:57,000
But by the time he got through his schooling, they didn't need pilots anymore.

127
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:05,000
And he had a course of very handy man and he knew how to fix anything.

128
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:09,000
So they put him in a good job for him.

129
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:12,000
But he did have to do some combat?

130
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:17,000
No, not really. It was never a shooting person.

131
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:20,000
He just worked on the airplanes.

132
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:26,000
But when they walked around the island, they were exposed to jacks sometimes.

133
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:36,000
And I know he said that he'd dug some holes to hide in, if they were around.

134
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:41,000
But he wasn't in a situation where he was particularly traumatized when he came back.

135
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:43,000
He was in pretty good shape.

136
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:45,000
Well, he was in pretty good shape.

137
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:50,000
But he told me that when he came back and of course he'd lost his dad.

138
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:55,000
And so his mother wanted a lot of things done around the house.

139
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:00,000
And he said he didn't go out at all. He just wanted to stay home.

140
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:05,000
So he did a lot of repair work around the house that she wanted done for.

141
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:10,000
I think it was over six months that he just didn't do anything.

142
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Yeah, he needed to make a transition.

143
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:17,000
Yes. And then when he came back to school,

144
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:23,000
he was ready to get on with his life.

145
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:31,000
And his goal when he came back to school was to get a Tomlinson commission.

146
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:37,000
And it must be a thing of the past because I asked some military men not long ago

147
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:42,000
if they knew what a Tomlinson commission was and they didn't know anything about it.

148
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:54,000
But as I understood it at the time, it was a commission given to people with proper qualifications

149
00:12:54,000 --> 00:13:01,000
that would give them a permanent place in the military,

150
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:08,000
not a reserve commission which most of the kids who go through ROTC receive.

151
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:12,000
So that was quite an honor to get that.

152
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:17,000
And then we were going to be married in June.

153
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:25,000
And he received the Tomlinson commission just in very short time, maybe the middle of May.

154
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:31,000
Before we were to be married and he said he never consulted me but he just said,

155
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:37,000
I just figured you wouldn't make a very good military wife and I turned it down.

156
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:41,000
That's interesting. Now, why do you think he thought that was it the moving around part

157
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:43,000
that he thought she was looking for?

158
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:48,000
I think so. And I also think that he blamed it on me a little bit.

159
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:55,000
But I think that the time he decided to get married that he wanted to be settled down,

160
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:00,000
he didn't want to travel. So I think it was a little bit of both.

161
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:03,000
That's a hard life really definitely.

162
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:05,000
Yes, it is.

163
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:13,000
So what was his major in college?

164
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
Industrial engineering.

165
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:19,000
Oh, interesting. I didn't realize that.

166
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:24,000
And he worked for a high-ster company the first year or so.

167
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:28,000
We moved after we went on our honey.

168
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:34,000
Well, I don't know whether I covered this with weight or not but we were.

169
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:41,000
He was commissioned in the morning and he got the Tomlinson commission.

170
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:50,000
At noon he was graduated from Oregon State and it was 107 degrees in Corvallis.

171
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:58,000
At that time they graduated from the men's gym which is now something else I don't know.

172
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:05,000
And they had ice, big 50-pound box of ice in all the windows.

173
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:12,000
And I remember looking at his car he had perspired clear through all his car.

174
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:15,000
And then we were married in the evening.

175
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:16,000
Oh my goodness.

176
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:18,000
That was a big day.

177
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:19,000
It was.

178
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:20,000
Had you planned it that way?

179
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,000
Did you know the graduation was going to happen?

180
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:23,000
Yes.

181
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:26,000
Oh, that sounds like a stressful way to do things.

182
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:29,000
But after the honeymoon, why?

183
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:38,000
And that was also a little crisis because we had the van port flood at that moment.

184
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:39,000
Tell me what that is.

185
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:45,000
And so we were going up to Lake Quenalt.

186
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:48,000
We had to get up to Washington.

187
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:57,000
And so Kerman said, well we were going to spend the first night in Salem because we didn't want to drive very far.

188
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:02,000
And after the wedding and all the day we had.

189
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:08,000
So there was a thunderstorm that night because of the heat.

190
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:16,000
And when we drove up the highway there were power lines coming down and flopping on the highway.

191
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:23,000
And I thought, oh we're going to get electrocuted before we ever have a honeymoon.

192
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:24,000
But we did.

193
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:25,000
We made it to Salem.

194
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:32,000
Then we knew that the bridges and we're all closed.

195
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:39,000
So the only way to get north was through long view or bridge of the gods.

196
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:41,000
And so he said, which do you want to do?

197
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And I said, well we're off on a holiday.

198
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:46,000
Let's just go to the bridge of the gods.

199
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:49,000
I've never been across the bridge of the gods.

200
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:50,000
And he said, okay.

201
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:52,000
So we went up there.

202
00:16:52,000 --> 00:17:00,000
And we came around and we got as far as some place in Washington.

203
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:02,000
I can't remember the name.

204
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:04,000
Good river is close to the river.

205
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:08,000
Kay, it was something Kay.

206
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:11,000
I can look on a map and find it.

207
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:13,000
But anyway we got that far.

208
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:16,000
And the town was underwater.

209
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:23,000
So then we had to turn around and go back over the bridge of the gods down to long view and then across.

210
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:24,000
Wow.

211
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:26,000
And we called that wet flood, the Vanport flood.

212
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:28,000
Vanport flood.

213
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And that was a big major.

214
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:38,000
It was where a lot of people lived during the war.

215
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:41,000
It was kind of low income housing.

216
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:44,000
And it all flooded.

217
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,000
And you never heard of that Vanport flood?

218
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:48,000
I am embarrassed to say that that happened.

219
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:51,000
Well, it's very well known.

220
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:55,000
Like a lot of people.

221
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:57,000
So was it a section of Portland?

222
00:17:57,000 --> 00:17:58,000
Yes.

223
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:01,000
It was out by Jensen Beach.

224
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:03,000
Oh, look that up and read about it a little bit.

225
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:06,000
So anyway, you were going to tell me a little bit about your wedding.

226
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:07,000
Oh, yes.

227
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:09,000
It was at the Presbyterian church.

228
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:10,000
That's correct.

229
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:18,000
And at first I said to my parents that I don't want to be married in the Presbyterian church

230
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:23,000
because at that time it's been remodeled since it was pretty barney.

231
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:26,000
And that cold I felt.

232
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:29,000
And I just didn't want to be married there.

233
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:32,000
Well, we got to looking at the wedding list.

234
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:36,000
And of course, Kermit's family was from Monmouth.

235
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:41,000
And my family had lived here forever.

236
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:49,000
And the guest list was getting so big that that was about the only place that we could have the wedding.

237
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:50,000
So bless my father.

238
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:53,000
He decided that he could fix it.

239
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:57,000
So that morning he and I don't know who else.

240
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:00,000
I wasn't aware of it all going on.

241
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:06,000
Somebody helped him and they brought in about 50 fertries.

242
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,000
There were a lot of them.

243
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:12,000
And they put it all around the front of the church.

244
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:16,000
And it was so hot that they...

245
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:21,000
And it was in June when the new growth was on the fertries.

246
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:29,000
And so they wilted and it looked like a little ornament on each limb of the trees.

247
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:31,000
It was just beautiful.

248
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:33,000
And so it was on the inside of the church.

249
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:34,000
Yes.

250
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:38,000
They brought them all in and put them up inside the church.

251
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:44,000
And as I say, all the fertries, because it was so hot, they just wilted.

252
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:49,000
And all those little new growth on it, just hung down.

253
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:52,000
And they looked like a little ornament.

254
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:55,000
It was just really quite effective.

255
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:00,000
And then we had white...

256
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:08,000
One of those white flowers that you take to cemetery in June from Memorial Day.

257
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:18,000
Not chrysanthemums, but not down.

258
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:22,000
I don't know either, but I can look it up.

259
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:25,000
I'll let you do that.

260
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:29,000
I may be able to think of it before we get through.

261
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:35,000
But anyway, it was really pretty all white and then the shades of green.

262
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:39,000
It was really quite lovely and people were quite impressed by it.

263
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:41,000
Yes, and so perfect for your family.

264
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,000
Yes, it was.

265
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:44,000
That's a nice statement.

266
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:46,000
So tell me about your dress.

267
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:47,000
Is it something that...

268
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:49,000
Well, I made my dress.

269
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:56,000
So in those days, there were the bridal stores that there are now.

270
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:03,000
And I wanted to wear my mother's wedding dress, but it was too small.

271
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:07,000
My mother was a very petite lady when she was married.

272
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:13,000
But she had a lot of lace on her dress and also on the veil.

273
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:22,000
So I took the lace and put some sheer yoke on my dress.

274
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:27,000
And the lace was from her wedding dress.

275
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:32,000
So it was quite a sentimental affair.

276
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:39,000
But I made it because I was a home economist and I sewed.

277
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:44,000
And there were patterns and sewing books to use.

278
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:47,000
So it worked out just fine.

279
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:57,000
And then her veil had been kind of eaten through the ears with different, I suppose, balls or something.

280
00:21:57,000 --> 00:21:58,000
I don't know.

281
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:04,000
And anyway, I used all the lace from her veil around the edge of my veil.

282
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:06,000
So I thought that was quite nice.

283
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:09,000
Yeah, it sounds very touching.

284
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:12,000
Was it a large group?

285
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:16,000
Was it your family or were there friends and community members too?

286
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:23,000
Well, there weren't too many because there was my father's sister and her husband.

287
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:28,000
And then my grandmother was...

288
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:35,000
My father's mother was alive at that time.

289
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:40,000
And her wish was that she lived to see me married.

290
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:42,000
And she got her wish.

291
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:46,000
She came in a wheelchair.

292
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:51,000
And she couldn't see very well.

293
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:54,000
But we had a nice conversation.

294
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:58,000
And during our honeymoon she died.

295
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:04,000
And so we had to come home from our honeymoon to go to her funeral.

296
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:09,000
It was wonderful that she got her wish.

297
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:11,000
Yes.

298
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:17,000
So there's so much planning and such that goes into weddings these days.

299
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:20,000
It seems like it's just a huge endeavor.

300
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:24,000
Did you have a big build up to it?

301
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:25,000
Well, no.

302
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:30,000
I think in those days it wasn't a three day affair like it is now.

303
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:35,000
Well, as I say, we were pretty busy all day.

304
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:40,000
But we just had the wedding and then reception.

305
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:43,000
And people didn't stay long at that reception.

306
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:45,000
It was too hot.

307
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:47,000
But we had cake.

308
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:50,000
I think we just had cake and punch.

309
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:53,000
There at the church.

310
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:57,000
Well, that sounds just right because then you could get out and get on your way.

311
00:23:57,000 --> 00:23:58,000
Yes.

312
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:03,000
So now they do a breakfast after the wedding and all that stuff.

313
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:04,000
Dinner beforehand.

314
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:06,000
Oh, yeah.

315
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:09,000
My daughter went to a wedding not so long ago.

316
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:11,000
It was in Hawaii.

317
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:16,000
They had a big groom's dinner.

318
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:21,000
Yes, my folks did a groom's dinner the night before.

319
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:26,000
And we had a lot of the fraternity boys.

320
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:32,000
And some of the family, but there were only just those few people.

321
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:39,000
I don't think my grandmother came to that because she was too frail.

322
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:51,000
But we did have, and they gave it because her mother was in, she lived in Canvy.

323
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:54,000
So it wasn't convenient for her to do it.

324
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:57,000
And those days we didn't go to restaurants.

325
00:24:57,000 --> 00:24:59,000
It was all done in your home.

326
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:00,000
Sure.

327
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:01,000
I've got more of a family event.

328
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:06,000
Well, you know, we only had just one or two restaurants in Carvalas.

329
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:08,000
Customs in and out.

330
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:10,000
The Gables, that was about it.

331
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:12,000
The Gables was an original.

332
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:14,000
Interesting.

333
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:19,000
Have any of your, did either of your daughters use your dress as a wedding dress?

334
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:20,000
No.

335
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:21,000
No.

336
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:22,000
They never did.

337
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:23,000
They wanted their own.

338
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:25,000
Do you still have that dress?

339
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:26,000
Yes, I do.

340
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:31,000
I'd love to have a picture of you and your dress and this.

341
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:33,000
It won't fit now.

342
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:36,000
I don't mean a curved picture.

343
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:39,000
But I do have a picture.

344
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:40,000
Good.

345
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:42,000
Wonderful.

346
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:47,000
So you went off and did your honeymoon and then he ended up in a first job in Portland.

347
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:50,000
And how did he get that job with Heister?

348
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:55,000
Well, I think through the college in those days we had placement people.

349
00:25:55,000 --> 00:26:01,000
I know I was placed in a job by a placement person on the campus.

350
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:08,000
And I presume that's how he got his job and he worked for Heister for...

351
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:10,000
We lived there.

352
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:18,000
We lived in an apartment, a very small apartment for a few months.

353
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:25,000
Her mother wanted to do three things before she died.

354
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:29,000
And I'll try to remember what they were.

355
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:37,000
She wanted to go down to see her other son, Norman, who lived in California.

356
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:42,000
She wanted to fly in an airplane.

357
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:49,000
What was the third thing she wanted to do?

358
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:52,000
Well, she did all three anyway, whatever they were.

359
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:54,000
It may come to you too.

360
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:01,000
And so she said, why don't you and Kermit live in my house while I go do these things?

361
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:08,000
Because she spent probably a month maybe more down in California.

362
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:10,000
And she had a garden.

363
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:11,000
She was a great gardener.

364
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:15,000
Of course, can be soil is wonderful for gardens.

365
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:20,000
And so we stayed at the house and took care of the garden.

366
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:29,000
And I did a lot of canning for her and got things made use of what was in the garden.

367
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:34,000
And then she came home.

368
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:36,000
And I had an offer.

369
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:40,000
I think maybe I told Wade this.

370
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:46,000
I had an offer to go down to the dowels.

371
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:53,000
And do a...

372
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:57,000
Sometimes I have trouble with getting the right words out.

373
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:00,000
I was judging a fair.

374
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:07,000
And so I said to her, wouldn't you like to go with me?

375
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:09,000
That'd be a nice trip for you.

376
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:11,000
I'm just going for the day.

377
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:14,000
And she said, oh, she'd love to.

378
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:16,000
Well, she went with me.

379
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:20,000
And I judged pillow slips among them.

380
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:25,000
And broader pillow slips among many other things.

381
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:31,000
And I gave first prize to the white embroidered pillow slips.

382
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:36,000
Because a lot of the women had done multi-colored ones.

383
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:39,000
And they were pretty bad.

384
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:42,000
Excuse me.

385
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:44,000
Hello.

386
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:46,000
Yes.

387
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:50,000
Yes, Rebecca. How are you this morning?

388
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:52,000
Well, I'm fine, Rebecca.

389
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:56,000
But I have a lady sitting here now that's doing an interview with me.

390
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:03,000
So I really can't talk.

391
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:04,000
Oh, good. Good.

392
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:10,000
Well, now when are you in a week from Friday?

393
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:17,000
Well, would you put a little tickler on your counter to call me when you get home so that we can...

394
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:20,000
I can come down and talk with you.

395
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:23,000
Okay. Thanks.

396
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:25,000
Oh, we had a good time, didn't we?

397
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:27,000
I did.

398
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:30,000
Okay. Bye. Bye.

399
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:31,000
Sorry.

400
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:35,000
That's great.

401
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:37,000
Can you give the prize to the white pillow slips?

402
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:38,000
Yes.

403
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:46,000
So anyway, there was quite some discussion, apparently, about this judge who was doing this.

404
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:53,000
And she sat in the corner and listened to her new daughter-in-law, you know, being criticized.

405
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:59,000
She could hardly wait to get in the car and tell me that he's women, that's it.

406
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:01,000
And she was just laughing.

407
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:04,000
And she just thought that was the funniest thing.

408
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:09,000
They could get that excited about their real emotions.

409
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:12,000
She had quite a sense of humor.

410
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
She used it often.

411
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:18,000
She just had a great sense of humor.

412
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:21,000
We got along just great.

413
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:24,000
Well, it's a shame that you didn't get to spend more time with her.

414
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:25,000
Yes.

415
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:35,000
And then I suppose we better put in something about how she died because it wasn't more than a couple of months.

416
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:42,000
I'd forgotten when she died, but she didn't last more than a couple of months after she came home.

417
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:46,000
And we got a call when we were in Portland.

418
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:52,000
We had moved from the house where we lived while she was away.

419
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:55,000
And we got in our department in Portland.

420
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:00,000
We lived where the Safeway is now in Lloyd Center.

421
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:06,000
And we got a call one morning about 530 or 6.

422
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:12,000
And the landlady's, you know, telephones were hard to get right after the war.

423
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:15,000
And she had no telephone in her house.

424
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:20,000
And we had no telephone in our house in our apartment.

425
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:26,000
But the landlady called and she tapped on our door and she said,

426
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:30,000
your mother has had a heart attack and you need to go.

427
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:33,000
And so we just dressed and left.

428
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:41,000
And we got there, she had the heart attack and gotten up and tried to make it over to the neighbors,

429
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:44,000
but had fallen in her garden.

430
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:50,000
And the neighbors had found her early in the morning, fortunately.

431
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:55,000
And so they got her back into the house and in bed.

432
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:59,000
And of course we got there and called the doctor.

433
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:06,000
And you know, what we know about heart now is just like night and day.

434
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:11,000
Because we didn't know the minutes where seconds were important at that time.

435
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:17,000
And the doctors at that era made house calls.

436
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:20,000
So the doctor came to the house.

437
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:25,000
And of course by that time, you know, she had a lot of problems.

438
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:29,000
Well, she lasted about two or three days.

439
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:34,000
I remember, Kermit went back to her apartment to clean out the refrigerator

440
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:41,000
and get things squared away because we just left and bring some clothes for us to wear.

441
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:52,000
And so when he was gone to Portland to get those things taken care of,

442
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:54,000
she had another attack.

443
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:01,000
And I was feeding her some apple sauce because I had made some from her own apples.

444
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:04,000
And she said, oh, it smells so good.

445
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:06,000
I just would like to have a taste.

446
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:09,000
And so I said, well, fine, I'll fix you some.

447
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:11,000
And I was feeding her.

448
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:16,000
And all of a sudden she just died.

449
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:22,000
And so Kermit came home about the time that that happened.

450
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:26,000
And he immediately called the doctor.

451
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:30,000
And he said, well, she's gone.

452
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:33,000
So sorry.

453
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:39,000
Hello.

454
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:41,000
Hi there.

455
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:43,000
How are you?

456
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:45,000
Good.

457
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:50,000
But I'm with a lady here that I need to...

458
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:57,000
She's doing an interview with me and I don't have much time to talk, unfortunately.

459
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:01,000
Where are you now?

460
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:06,000
Okay.

461
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:13,000
Well, I'll call you tonight.

462
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:18,000
I mailed the package to Micah today about the coat.

463
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:23,000
Yeah, so he'll get it in a couple of days.

464
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:24,000
Good.

465
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:34,000
Well, I said I took all the things off of the batches and then I sent it to the cleaners.

466
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:37,000
So it's all ready to go.

467
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:38,000
All right.

468
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:45,000
Well, I'll try and call you around five o'clock work.

469
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:46,000
Okay.

470
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:48,000
I'll give you a call.

471
00:34:48,000 --> 00:34:50,000
Okay.

472
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:51,000
I'm sorry.

473
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:52,000
That was my grandson.

474
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:54,000
Quite all right.

475
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:03,000
So you were saying that Kermit got there just as she asked away.

476
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:04,000
Yes.

477
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:12,000
And I didn't know anything about death and he held her tongue down.

478
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:16,000
It was pretty awful.

479
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:24,000
And we had to call his brother in California and they came up and then we divided all the stuff.

480
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:28,000
And that's how we got all the furniture because they didn't want the furniture.

481
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:31,000
They'd been married for a number of years.

482
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:37,000
And he was the oldest brother and Kermit was the youngest.

483
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:43,000
They said, you just take all the furniture, so that's what we did.

484
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:48,000
So do you think you said she had some a few wishes of things she wanted to do before she died?

485
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:50,000
Do you think she had a sense that she was?

486
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:57,000
I think she knew that and I really think that Kermit sensed that he was not going to live very long.

487
00:35:57,000 --> 00:35:58,000
Really?

488
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:04,000
Because he was so always so insistent that I know everything about our business.

489
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:08,000
And so and both his parents had died of heart attack.

490
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:14,000
His father fell off of, he was milking a cow and fell off the stool and died.

