00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:04,000
But Kermit thought it was the thing to do.

503
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:11,000
We had two children by then and he thought it was the thing to do.

504
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:19,000
And my dad was putting a lot of pressure on him to come back and start a plywood plant.

505
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:20,000
Oh, interesting.

506
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:25,000
And of course Kermit had the industrial engineering training.

507
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:36,000
So there were ten men who put their money together and built the plywood plant.

508
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:45,000
And Kermit designed it and was in charge of it because the rest of the men all had other jobs.

509
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:49,000
So he did that for three or four years.

510
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:52,000
Don't remember just how long.

511
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:59,000
But then the plywood market went kaput.

512
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:06,000
And so they sold it to somebody, can't remember.

513
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:13,000
So then he Kermit went into partnership with a man, Gordon Larson.

514
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:19,000
And that's, you know, Beverly Larson, who runs the O'Mail School.

515
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:25,000
Well, it was her father that was in partnership with Kermit.

516
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:30,000
And my dad was sort of putting up the money for this mill.

517
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:41,000
Gordon had had a mill out, well, at the Y in Pholomath, he was on the wall port side.

518
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:42,000
I don't know.

519
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:45,000
It wasn't very far up that road.

520
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:48,000
He had always had a saw mill.

521
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:55,000
And so, but they decided they built it down here at 53rd and reservoir road.

522
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:00,000
And so Kermit designed that mill.

523
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:09,000
And then they built it and ran it for, I would say maybe eight or nine years.

524
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:25,000
And then they had a, I wouldn't say a, well, they disagreed on just a little bit about how it should be run.

525
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:30,000
And so Kermit said he'd like to buy him out.

526
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:33,000
Gordon didn't have the money to buy him out.

527
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:39,000
So Kermit did buy the mill out.

528
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:46,000
And then Gordon died probably maybe six months after that.

529
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:48,000
That was all settled.

530
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:52,000
Because, of course, they had to divide up all the timberland and everything.

531
00:39:52,000 --> 00:39:53,000
Oh, I see.

532
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:56,000
They had properties that went with the mill.

533
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:05,000
They bought a lot of timberland in order to have timber in the winter time when they couldn't log other places.

534
00:40:05,000 --> 00:40:11,000
They bought timberland that could be logged in the winter time.

535
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:22,000
So, that was very fortunate that we got all that done before he died.

536
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:24,000
Yes, that would have been nice.

537
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:28,000
He died of hard attack, too, as I remember it.

538
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:34,000
You could check with them about that, but I think that he did.

539
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:36,000
So that mill's not there anymore, is it?

540
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:38,000
No, it is.

541
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:41,000
It's where they started to run sheep.

542
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:44,000
Yeah, I know there's just a little organic meat there.

543
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:47,000
They couldn't do it because it was annexed.

544
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:56,000
Yeah, when I ran the property for a number of years after my husband died,

545
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:01,000
I rented it out to various people who ran the mill.

546
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:05,000
And then timber prices weren't very good.

547
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:14,000
And the last people that owned it, it was just ready to not be run anymore.

548
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:28,000
And so, one day, they were putting in the water pipe down reservoir road,

549
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:36,000
and then it came into the fairgrounds, and they wanted some place to dump the dirt.

550
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:43,000
And so, I said, well, dump it in the pond because I just assumed fill in those ponds.

551
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:53,000
Well, it seemed as though that was not the thing to do because there are rules about filling ponds I found out.

552
00:41:53,000 --> 00:41:59,000
Well, one day, I spent, I don't know how long on the telephone.

553
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:07,000
It was all one afternoon and into the next day, talking to governmental agencies.

554
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:13,000
And finally, I got a hold of some, I don't remember which one.

555
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:19,000
But they said, oh, Mrs. Roth, we don't talk to owners, we just talk to lawyers.

556
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:26,000
And that was the living end. I just decided I wasn't going to have anything to do with that.

557
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:31,000
So, my, I was moping to my son about it.

558
00:42:31,000 --> 00:42:34,000
And he said, oh, mom, you shouldn't have that stress.

559
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:37,000
I said, I'll take over running it.

560
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:42,000
So anyway, he tried to run it for, I don't know, four or five years.

561
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:46,000
And he was in California, and it was just too much.

562
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:49,000
So he finally sold it.

563
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:53,000
And that's when they started to run the goats.

564
00:42:53,000 --> 00:42:57,000
And then they found out they couldn't run the goats because it was in it.

565
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:00,000
He had annexed it.

566
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:05,000
So now it's in city, within city limits.

567
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:07,000
Yeah, yeah, it's in the city limits.

568
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:09,000
That's interesting.

569
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:16,000
And it's very odd because soon after, can got through, sold it.

570
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:23,000
And now, they're, you know, they put in all that lovely area in front of the fairgrounds

571
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:25,000
and they've got the dirt over ready.

572
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:31,000
And they're going to run the street 50th, it's going to go up over the rail road.

573
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:34,000
And they're going to do that right away.

574
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:37,000
Oh, I didn't realize that.

575
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:39,000
That's interesting.

576
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:42,000
So bad at the city.

577
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:45,000
You know, one thing after another.

578
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:48,000
So he, so current was, as long as we're talking about his career,

579
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:52,000
I can ask you the rest of my questions about, about his career.

580
00:43:52,000 --> 00:44:02,000
So he then stayed at that mill till, I know this.

581
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:05,000
He wanted himself in 67 then.

582
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:07,000
And then did he stay with the mill?

583
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:09,000
All the rest of his life?

584
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:10,000
Yes.

585
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:14,000
Yes, he shut it down after he'd run it 12 years.

586
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:19,000
And we didn't do anything with it.

587
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:27,000
I guess he, I can't remember whether he rented it to anybody or not.

588
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:32,000
But he played the stock market and he was very sharp about it.

589
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:40,000
He would get up in the morning and look at all the listings in the paper.

590
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:46,000
And he made a lot of money on the stock market because he just had a feel for it.

591
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:54,000
And one time we bought Fuji Photo Stock.

592
00:44:54,000 --> 00:45:02,000
And we made a lot of money on that because it was just when it was starting to come into the United States.

593
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:05,000
So he said, I think we should take a trip.

594
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:09,000
And I said, well, we made our money on Fuji Photo.

595
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:12,000
I think we should go to Japan.

596
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:14,000
And so we did.

597
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:16,000
And that was real fun.

598
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:19,000
We had a lovely, lovely trip.

599
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:22,000
So was that when you had all four children?

600
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:24,000
Did you take children with you on the trip?

