Yes.

731
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:35,000
And I could be very upset with my nephews.

732
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:38,000
They had nothing to do with it.

733
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:46,000
It was all my dad's object to leave that as a unit.

734
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:48,000
And he didn't want.

735
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:52,000
And he didn't really appreciate women either.

736
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:56,000
He didn't like the fact that women were in the forestry school.

737
00:54:56,000 --> 00:55:06,000
And he didn't really like my sister-in-law got interested in the timber business.

738
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:11,000
And he really didn't like that either.

739
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:15,000
He was of German.

740
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:16,000
Yeah.

741
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:18,000
Traditional.

742
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:20,000
The oldest son.

743
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:22,000
Yeah.

744
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:28,000
Yeah, that's, like you say, that's a longstanding tradition of patriarchy.

745
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:32,000
Yeah, that's right.

746
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:36,000
Well, you did very well.

747
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:46,000
Yes, probably by German's hard work in the stock market and buying things at the right time and that kind of thing.

748
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:51,000
And does the Roth property services business still exist?

749
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:53,000
Oh, yes.

750
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:55,000
That's what I do.

751
00:55:55,000 --> 00:55:57,000
I do three times a week.

752
00:55:57,000 --> 00:55:58,000
I work at that.

753
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:03,000
I have a bookkeeper that comes and keeps track of things.

754
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:06,000
And I manage the properties.

755
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:12,000
And I have four major properties that I'm leaving to.

756
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:17,000
One to each one of my children.

757
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:21,000
So how did you learn how to do all that real estate business?

758
00:56:21,000 --> 00:56:23,000
I don't know.

759
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:30,000
I think it was by Osmosis from learning from hearing my dad speak about it.

760
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:35,000
I think I just absorbed the way it was supposed to be done.

761
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:41,000
Because of course, his talk at the dinner table was always about business.

762
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:42,000
Yeah.

763
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:47,000
And I think I must have just sort of absorbed it.

764
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:51,000
Did you increment work together in the early years when you were finished?

765
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:52,000
Absolutely.

766
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:53,000
Yeah, absolutely.

767
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:54,000
We did.

768
00:56:54,000 --> 00:56:59,000
I remember one time we owned up that property down.

769
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:07,000
It's a corner of, it's where that painting pottery painting places.

770
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:08,000
Down town.

771
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:11,000
And we owned that building at one time.

772
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:18,000
And the real estate man, I remember this so vividly, he called up and he said,

773
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:20,000
did we want to sell it?

774
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:25,000
And Kermit put down the phone and he said, do we want to sell that?

775
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:32,000
Because there was a lot of agitation at the time that they were going to change downtown.

776
00:57:32,000 --> 00:57:40,000
And the Madison Avenue Task Force was in starting and they were going to do big things.

777
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:49,000
And of course, the guy that's chairman of the Madison Avenue Task Force is a very good friends of ours and still friends.

778
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:53,000
But I didn't always agree with what they were doing.

779
00:57:53,000 --> 00:58:05,000
And so I said to Kermit, you know, I think we're going to be charged a lot for doing makeover there.

780
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:10,000
And I said, what do they want to give us for it?

781
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:13,000
And so the realtor said, well, what do you take for it?

782
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:16,000
And we don't only held it a year or so.

783
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:20,000
And I said, well, 50,000 more than we want to pay for it.

784
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:26,000
And he said that my buyers will take it.

785
00:58:26,000 --> 00:58:28,000
But 10 minute conversation.

786
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:35,000
I thought that that was a pretty good way to make 50,000 bucks.

787
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:38,000
Well, so the two of you were sort of a business team.

788
00:58:38,000 --> 00:58:43,000
Yes, we'd always kind of saw eye to eye on how we did it.

789
00:58:43,000 --> 00:58:47,000
So forth, we never had any discussions.

790
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:49,000
We just talk about it.

791
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:51,000
That was it.

792
00:58:51,000 --> 00:58:53,000
Go on from there.

793
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:59,000
So did he ever regret leaving me off being an industrial engineer?

794
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:01,000
No, I don't think so.

795
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:05,000
No, I think it was very much.

796
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:10,000
I think he really enjoyed the business aspect of it.

797
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:11,000
He thinks so.

798
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:13,000
Sounds like he was a natural at that.

799
00:59:13,000 --> 00:59:15,000
Yes.

800
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:20,000
Yeah, I'm sure he did.

801
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:23,000
So you had your first two children there in Portland?

802
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:24,000
Yes.

803
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:27,000
And then we moved down here.

804
00:59:27,000 --> 00:59:42,000
And we had a house down on 10th and Adams.

805
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:45,000
Right by the railroad.

806
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:46,000
Pacific through.

807
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:48,000
You remember that?

808
00:59:48,000 --> 00:59:50,000
Yeah, about word.

809
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:52,000
Yeah, where it was right there.

810
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:59,000
And we bought the house because it had enough bedrooms for us to put the furniture.

811
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:09,000
And then my dad was developing Cedarhurst which is the corner of 35th and Harrison.

812
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:14,000
And he had, I think it's 32 acres in there.

813
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:20,000
And he developed that with a division of Ben Buren and Jackson.

814
01:00:20,000 --> 01:00:36,000
And he gave us a hunk of property down on Jackson Street because he'd given my brother a piece of that area between Ben Buren and Jackson.

815
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:41,000
But clear at the end of where the dairy barns were.

816
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:47,000
And of course they lived at the last house out on Harrison.

817
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:50,000
They built that when I was in high school.

818
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:52,000
So that's where we lived.

819
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:59,000
So after we moved back to Curvellis while he gave Curvell and I this piece at the end of Jackson.

820
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:04,000
And Curvellis just took a year off and built that house.

821
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:08,000
And he built it with the help of one carpenter.

822
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:12,000
And I think he only subcontracted.

823
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:23,000
He did the wiring so he subcontracted the heating and the water.

824
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:25,000
Seems to me there was something else.

825
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:30,000
He did all the rest of it himself because he was capable of doing that.

826
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:33,000
And I back primed all that siding.

827
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:40,000
I would go out there after the children got up from their naps in the afternoon.

828
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:43,000
And I'd go out and they'd play in the yard.

829
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:46,000
Well, I was painting.

830
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:51,000
So we did it together but it mostly curmed.

831
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:54,000
That's impressive.

832
01:01:54,000 --> 01:01:56,000
Is that house still standing?

833
01:01:56,000 --> 01:02:00,000
Yes, the Kines lived there.

834
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:03,000
Yes, in fact it was written up in the paper recently.

835
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:07,000
Yes, I remember seeing your name in that article.

836
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:10,000
And how long did you live in that house then?

837
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:12,000
We lived there 35 years.

838
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:14,000
So all the way through your childhood.

839
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:20,000
Yes, and he died from that house and I lived there six years after he died.

840
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:27,000
But you know, it was a seven bedroom house and it was a little big for one lady.

841
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:37,000
And so when my last one married, I knew she wanted to be married from that house.

842
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:39,000
She's a very sentimental girl.

843
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:45,000
And so as soon as she was married, then I thought, boy, it's time to take care of Jean.

844
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:48,000
And so I then built this house.

845
01:02:48,000 --> 01:02:51,000
I see.

846
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:55,000
I built this house.

847
01:02:55,000 --> 01:03:01,000
But Kathy in the meantime had gotten an architectural degree.

848
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:08,000
And so she designed the house pretty much for me and then built her build it.

849
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:11,000
Wow, wonderful.

850
01:03:11,000 --> 01:03:17,000
So I really supervised all the building of this house.

851
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:18,000
Do you like building?

852
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:20,000
Yes, I do.

853
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:24,000
And then later, I built the house at Newport.

854
01:03:24,000 --> 01:03:27,000
So I built two houses.

855
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:29,000
That's impressive.

856
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:32,000
I helped my husband and I built our house.

857
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:34,000
And I always think I would never do that again.

858
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:36,000
But some people really enjoy it.

859
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:37,000
Oh, I did.

860
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:39,000
I just thoroughly enjoyed it.

861
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:40,000
Yeah.

862
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:42,000
So many decisions to make.

863
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:43,000
Oh, yeah.

864
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:44,000
But I loved it.

865
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:45,000
I thought it was great.

866
01:03:45,000 --> 01:03:48,000
Cool, wonderful.

867
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:49,000
Good.

868
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:56,000
So I'm trying to envision your life here in Corvallis with four children all pretty close to the same ages.

869
01:03:56,000 --> 01:04:04,000
Well, they were actually ten years apart because the first three were two years apart.

870
01:04:04,000 --> 01:04:09,000
Then we waited four years and then had the next one.

871
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:11,000
But still you had your hands full.

872
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:12,000
Yes, yes, I did.

873
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:14,000
I was busy with the children.

874
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:17,000
Did you start working before you had children?

875
01:04:17,000 --> 01:04:18,000
Yes, I did.

876
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:34,000
But I did a lot of not only volunteering, but I did some teaching at the high school with what do they call that?

877
01:04:34,000 --> 01:04:41,000
Well, it's where you teach certain courses to adults.

878
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:44,000
I don't know what they call that now.

879
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:46,000
It used to be night school.

880
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:47,000
Yeah.

881
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:48,000
Something like that.

882
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:50,000
But now it does have another name.

883
01:04:50,000 --> 01:04:51,000
You're right.

884
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:53,000
Yeah, and I don't know what that is.

885
01:04:53,000 --> 01:04:58,000
But I taught Pendleton Jackets were very popular.

886
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:02,000
And so I taught a class on Pendleton Jackets.

887
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:03,000
And sewing them.

888
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:07,000
Uh-huh.

889
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:13,000
Well, Pendleton Jacket had a lot of the principles of sewing.

890
01:05:13,000 --> 01:05:15,000
You know, the pockets and the...

891
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:18,000
But it wasn't really complicated.

892
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:19,000
Really?

893
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:22,000
But it had a lot of principles of sewing.

894
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:31,000
And so I found that very much fun to teach people the basics.

895
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:35,000
So what kind of things did your family do?

896
01:05:35,000 --> 01:05:40,000
Were you able to do some things as a group with all six of you?

897
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:44,000
Or was that really too many kids to take little trips with and things like that?

898
01:05:44,000 --> 01:05:45,000
Oh, no.

899
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:49,000
We used to take the kids fishing every Sunday out at Quartz Creek.

900
01:05:49,000 --> 01:05:57,000
And then Bruce and Betty had a pond out...

901
01:05:58,000 --> 01:06:01,000
Well, it was out towards...

902
01:06:01,000 --> 01:06:02,000
Or was that out?

903
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:06,000
We went out to the Y and turned towards Wallport.

904
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:08,000
And what would we call that?

905
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:09,000
I don't know.

906
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:10,000
We had 34.

907
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:11,000
Yeah.

908
01:06:11,000 --> 01:06:15,000
And then they had some timberland out there that they had a pond on.

909
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:21,000
And there was a group of us that were quite...

910
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:26,000
It was the Jim Hallons, the RT Rises,

911
01:06:26,000 --> 01:06:45,000
the Budcrolls, and I guess that was at Bruce and Betty and us.

912
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:55,000
And we all worked together usually on Memorial Day 4th of July.

913
01:06:56,000 --> 01:07:00,000
What's the other holiday?

914
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:01,000
Labor Day.

915
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:02,000
Labor Day.

916
01:07:02,000 --> 01:07:03,000
Yeah.

917
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:05,000
Having a picnic out there.

918
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:07,000
We usually went out to the pond.

919
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:12,000
And then Kermit and I always took the kids and we went to...

920
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:16,000
We owned some property out...

921
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:17,000
Big elk.

922
01:07:17,000 --> 01:07:19,000
And we went out there, crawdading.

923
01:07:19,000 --> 01:07:20,000
Oh.

924
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:24,000
I got a great picture for you to put in the book on the crawdade.

925
01:07:24,000 --> 01:07:26,000
Oh, that sounds like fun.

926
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:31,000
And then we would ask somebody to come and eat crawdads.

927
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:32,000
We had crawdad feeds.

928
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:34,000
Big pile of crawdads, huh?

929
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:35,000
Uh-huh.

930
01:07:35,000 --> 01:07:36,000
Yeah, that's good.

931
01:07:36,000 --> 01:07:37,000
And then we...

932
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:40,000
As I say, we took the kids fishing up Quartz Creek.

933
01:07:40,000 --> 01:07:43,000
And then finally we got a boat.

934
01:07:43,000 --> 01:07:48,000
And by then the Rises had a place at Triangle Lake.

935
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:52,000
And we would go down there sometimes with our boat.

936
01:07:53,000 --> 01:07:55,000
And the kids water-skied.

937
01:07:55,000 --> 01:07:57,000
Oh, that's fun.

938
01:07:57,000 --> 01:07:58,000
That was when they were older maybe.

939
01:07:58,000 --> 01:07:59,000
Yes.

940
01:07:59,000 --> 01:08:04,000
So Kermit enjoyed his family life, it sounds like.

941
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:06,000
Oh yeah, he was a family man.

942
01:08:06,000 --> 01:08:08,000
I'll tell you.

943
01:08:08,000 --> 01:08:14,000
When he had the mill, he would sometimes go and get equipment from other mills

944
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:19,000
that were maybe no longer in service.

945
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:23,000
And he would say when he left, well,

946
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:28,000
I may not be back tonight because we might have trouble loading

947
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:30,000
or, you know, doing all this.

948
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:31,000
Almost always.

949
01:08:31,000 --> 01:08:33,000
He'd be home by midnight.

950
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:34,000
Uh-huh.

951
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:38,000
He'd never stayed over at any place.

952
01:08:38,000 --> 01:08:40,000
He just wanted to be there in the family.

953
01:08:40,000 --> 01:08:42,000
Yeah, he wanted to be home with the family.

954
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:46,000
I never had any concerns about him full of them.

955
01:08:46,000 --> 01:08:48,000
That's a good thing.

956
01:08:49,000 --> 01:08:53,000
No, he was definitely a family man.

957
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:54,000
Yeah.

958
01:08:54,000 --> 01:08:55,000
How about summer vacations?

959
01:08:55,000 --> 01:08:57,000
Did you guys ever take any trips?

960
01:08:57,000 --> 01:09:00,000
Not really as summer vacations.

961
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:06,000
But we, of course, had the place up the McKinsey,

962
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:11,000
which was really nice because he had been in the three seas up there,

963
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:13,000
which I told you about.

964
01:09:14,000 --> 01:09:18,000
And so we had that in common, too,

965
01:09:18,000 --> 01:09:20,000
because I taught school up there.

966
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:25,000
And so when we came to having a second home

967
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:29,000
or the second, whatever, it wasn't really a home,

968
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:32,000
it was a mobile home.

969
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:36,000
What do you call those?

970
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:38,000
Not a mobile home.

971
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:40,000
Yeah, I guess a mobile home.

972
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:41,000
Like a trailer.

973
01:09:41,000 --> 01:09:44,000
Yeah, it was a trailer like a place.

974
01:09:44,000 --> 01:09:48,000
And so when we bought the property to put the trailer on,

975
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:52,000
it was up the McKinsey because we'd been up there a lot.

976
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:54,000
Because we liked that area.

977
01:09:54,000 --> 01:09:58,000
So he had done trail building when he was there in the CCC?

978
01:09:58,000 --> 01:09:59,000
Yes.

979
01:09:59,000 --> 01:10:02,000
Interesting.

980
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:05,000
So that made for a good weekend getaway, probably?

981
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:06,000
Yes, it was.

982
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:08,000
It was a great place and the kids loved it.

983
01:10:08,000 --> 01:10:13,000
They loved to fish and we had three great fishing holes on that property.

984
01:10:13,000 --> 01:10:20,000
And we liked it so well that after we'd had the mobile home for a while,

985
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:25,000
it was a single wide and we decided that we liked it well enough

986
01:10:25,000 --> 01:10:30,000
and we wanted a fireplace because then it was cozy and we could use it in the wintertime.

987
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:34,000
So we had him haul away that one and bring up a double wide.

988
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:41,000
And I had that for a number of years after Kermit died.

989
01:10:41,000 --> 01:10:47,000
But all of a sudden there was a crack house moved in next door

990
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:53,000
and the people who owned that were from California and they rented it out.

991
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:57,000
And they brought up a lot of antiques and put in it.

992
01:10:57,000 --> 01:11:00,000
And it was just a gorgeous place.

993
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:07,000
They rented it out and it was a crack house and the people who had it needed wood

994
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:12,000
for their fireplace and they burned up all the antiques.

995
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:16,000
And I thought they'll probably be over here next.

996
01:11:16,000 --> 01:11:20,000
And I thought this is no place for me so I sold it.

997
01:11:20,000 --> 01:11:23,000
And it just killed me to sell it.

998
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:29,000
But it was 40 miles from any fire or police help.

999
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:30,000
Sure.

1000
01:11:30,000 --> 01:11:32,000
There was no place for a single woman.

1001
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:34,000
Yeah, that's understandable.

1002
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:40,000
So I had to give it up and I still hate it that we had to give that up.

1003
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:41,000
Yeah.

1004
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:44,000
Well, it sounds like you had lots of good years from it.

1005
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:45,000
No.

1006
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:46,000
That's a fun out there.

1007
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:48,000
You just have good memories.

1008
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:49,000
Yeah.

1009
01:11:49,000 --> 01:11:52,000
That's a good thing too.

1010
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:57,000
So you mentioned having your holidays with Bruce and Betty and I realized

1011
01:11:57,000 --> 01:12:04,000
I've never asked you what the transition was from when Bruce was sort of a nerdy kid who sat

1012
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:06,000
and read the encyclopedia all the time.

1013
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:08,000
When did you start to get close to him?

1014
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:16,000
Well, I think that Betty had a lot to do with that because she met Bruce because I had invited her

1015
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:22,000
to a summer party when we were in high school when she was going to college here.

1016
01:12:22,000 --> 01:12:25,000
Her father was an ROTC professor.

1017
01:12:25,000 --> 01:12:28,000
He was a military man.

1018
01:12:28,000 --> 01:12:34,000
And so Bruce offered to take her home after the summer.

1019
01:12:34,000 --> 01:12:41,000
And so they were soon married and then we did a lot of things together.

1020
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:49,000
We used to camp up at Spirit Lake where we had spent our Bruce and I had spent our childhood.

1021
01:12:49,000 --> 01:12:58,000
And so we did a lot of things together and then after Bruce died, Betty and I traveled a lot together.

1022
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:01,000
She brought the two of you closer together.

1023
01:13:01,000 --> 01:13:02,000
I think so.

1024
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:03,000
She brought him out of it.

1025
01:13:03,000 --> 01:13:08,000
He became a lot more after he was in the military.

1026
01:13:08,000 --> 01:13:11,000
I think he became a lot more social.

1027
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:15,000
Yeah, that's right because you had told me that you saw each other a lot in San Francisco too.

1028
01:13:15,000 --> 01:13:16,000
Yes.

1029
01:13:16,000 --> 01:13:17,000
That's right.

1030
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:18,000
Yeah.

1031
01:13:18,000 --> 01:13:25,000
Well, I'd love to hear a little bit about your children.

1032
01:13:25,000 --> 01:13:26,000
Okay.

1033
01:13:26,000 --> 01:13:28,000
Now we're early.

1034
01:13:28,000 --> 01:13:31,000
Well, I guess we should start early.

1035
01:13:31,000 --> 01:13:32,000
Okay.

1036
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:42,000
Well, Ken is the oldest and he was born in Portland and he was a good baby.

1037
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:45,000
He was a real...

1038
01:13:45,000 --> 01:13:48,000
We had him.

1039
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:49,000
I don't know.

1040
01:13:49,000 --> 01:13:51,000
Did we tell you?

1041
01:13:51,000 --> 01:13:56,000
Did we talk about the house that we had in Portland?

1042
01:13:56,000 --> 01:13:58,000
Not in great detail now.

1043
01:13:58,000 --> 01:14:08,000
Well, I told you that the first house was this apartment in the safe way where the safe way is now in the Lloyd Center.

1044
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:16,000
Well, then we moved over to the house that Ken was born from.

1045
01:14:16,000 --> 01:14:22,000
It was the Westminster Presbyterian Church Mance.

1046
01:14:22,000 --> 01:14:25,000
And it was a four-story house.

1047
01:14:25,000 --> 01:14:37,000
It had a basement, a main floor, a four-bedroom, a second floor, and a floor attic.

1048
01:14:37,000 --> 01:14:43,000
And so we called it the Roth Hotel because everybody came to see the...

1049
01:14:43,000 --> 01:14:46,000
that came to Portland, stayed with us.

1050
01:14:46,000 --> 01:14:47,000
Oh, your friends.

1051
01:14:47,000 --> 01:14:54,000
Well, Ken was born from there and then Craig came along.

1052
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:57,000
And that was when we...

1053
01:14:57,000 --> 01:15:02,000
Craig was about six months old when we moved to Corvallis.

1054
01:15:02,000 --> 01:15:11,000
And the house that we had there was all these floors.

1055
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:15,000
And it had six plugins.

1056
01:15:15,000 --> 01:15:19,000
Three of them, I think, were in the kitchen or maybe four.

1057
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:23,000
I would gas slides.

1058
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:26,000
A sink that was way down here.

1059
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:29,000
And I was pregnant with Craig.

1060
01:15:29,000 --> 01:15:36,000
And so Kermit took out the kitchen and put in what they called a Youngstown sink.

1061
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:41,000
And it was a sink with train boards, all one piece.

1062
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:46,000
And so he put it up so I could do dishes.

1063
01:15:46,000 --> 01:15:51,000
And then we had Craig.

1064
01:15:51,000 --> 01:15:57,000
And the thing that I remember about Ken when he was a little kid,

1065
01:15:57,000 --> 01:16:03,000
he had a rabbit that he loved and stuffed rabbit with stuffed.

1066
01:16:03,000 --> 01:16:09,000
And we had a backyard that we'd fenced.

1067
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:14,000
And so one day he was missing.

1068
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:22,000
The lady who had been helping me with Craig had left the gate open.

1069
01:16:22,000 --> 01:16:26,000
Well, I was just beside myself.

1070
01:16:26,000 --> 01:16:30,000
So we lived at Wider, I think it was.

1071
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:34,000
Anyway, it was two blocks down to Broadway.

1072
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:39,000
And here he was walking along with it holding the ears of the rabbit.

1073
01:16:39,000 --> 01:16:43,000
Just wandering around having a good time.

1074
01:16:43,000 --> 01:16:46,000
I was just friends.

1075
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:50,000
He was a very adventuresome child.

1076
01:16:50,000 --> 01:16:58,000
Then Craig came along and he was born with no bicep or no tricep and he's left arm.

1077
01:16:58,000 --> 01:17:02,000
They think I had interunion and polio.

1078
01:17:02,000 --> 01:17:12,000
That was when polio was so just becoming something that was everybody had to have a shot.

1079
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:16,000
So Craig was never athletic.

1080
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:20,000
Ken was always very athletic.

1081
01:17:20,000 --> 01:17:28,000
But Craig was when he'd ride a tricycle, he could do a tricycle pretty well.

1082
01:17:28,000 --> 01:17:30,000
But it came to bicycles.

1083
01:17:30,000 --> 01:17:36,000
He couldn't balance because he couldn't get that arm up.

1084
01:17:36,000 --> 01:17:43,000
So when he was in, we moved to Carvaleson.

1085
01:17:43,000 --> 01:17:53,000
I would say maybe six weeks or so into kindergarten.

1086
01:17:53,000 --> 01:18:00,000
The doctor that we had here in Carvales said I want you to go down to San Francisco

1087
01:18:00,000 --> 01:18:05,000
and go to Stanford Medical School and see what they can do for him.

1088
01:18:05,000 --> 01:18:09,000
Because he'd come in and he's a little facing, falling off his bicycle.

1089
01:18:09,000 --> 01:18:12,000
His face was all scarred up.

1090
01:18:12,000 --> 01:18:16,000
He just didn't have any balance.

1091
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:19,000
So we took him down there.

1092
01:18:19,000 --> 01:18:27,000
And the story that I love to tell about Craig is that my folks took us down to go.

1093
01:18:27,000 --> 01:18:31,000
We were going to fly down the San Francisco and it was fogged in.

1094
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:35,000
So we had to go on down and go by rail.

1095
01:18:35,000 --> 01:18:38,000
Well, Carmen and I were just beside ourselves.

1096
01:18:38,000 --> 01:18:44,000
This was a very nerve wracking experience for both of us to be taking this child down to the hospital.

1097
01:18:44,000 --> 01:18:49,000
We didn't know what was going to be the results of this.

1098
01:18:49,000 --> 01:18:57,000
So because my father was a T-totler, we didn't ever drink at home.

1099
01:18:57,000 --> 01:19:00,000
We always called it juice.

1100
01:19:00,000 --> 01:19:05,000
And so we went in to have some juice in the railroad car.

1101
01:19:05,000 --> 01:19:10,000
And we got a coke for Craig.

1102
01:19:10,000 --> 01:19:15,000
And the bartender there put a cherry in it.

1103
01:19:15,000 --> 01:19:22,000
And so when he came, he had the operation and came out of the anesthesia

1104
01:19:22,000 --> 01:19:27,000
and his legs and his arms were just thrashing.

1105
01:19:27,000 --> 01:19:34,000
And he yelled out, just in a loud voice, I want a cherry in my.

1106
01:19:34,000 --> 01:19:41,000
We were never able to tell my parents.

1107
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:46,000
But I think that's such a funny story.

1108
01:19:46,000 --> 01:19:50,000
The little things that were just in his subconscious at that time.

1109
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:53,000
So anyway, we got through that.

1110
01:19:53,000 --> 01:19:57,000
And then Kathy was born.

1111
01:19:57,000 --> 01:20:03,000
And we just expected another boy.

1112
01:20:03,000 --> 01:20:08,000
We were just thrilled to have this daughter.

1113
01:20:08,000 --> 01:20:13,000
And then Kim was born four years later.

1114
01:20:13,000 --> 01:20:18,000
And the girls were really quite good seamstresses.

1115
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:22,000
And I suppose that I taught them a lot of those things.

1116
01:20:22,000 --> 01:20:29,000
And they earned, they were blue ribbon winners for H,

1117
01:20:29,000 --> 01:20:33,000
for their dresses that they made.

1118
01:20:33,000 --> 01:20:42,000
And I think it was Kathy went on to state fair, got a blue ribbon.

1119
01:20:42,000 --> 01:20:46,000
They were really good seamstresses.

1120
01:20:46,000 --> 01:20:48,000
They don't do much.

1121
01:20:48,000 --> 01:20:51,000
I think Kathy does more than Kim.

1122
01:20:51,000 --> 01:20:58,000
But they were very active in 4-H.

1123
01:20:58,000 --> 01:21:01,000
So were you still involved in 4-H?

1124
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:03,000
Yes.

1125
01:21:03,000 --> 01:21:08,000
And later when I was on the 4-H,

1126
01:21:08,000 --> 01:21:15,000
I was a trustee for the 4-H, Steve board that they had.

1127
01:21:15,000 --> 01:21:23,000
And my dad was very instrumental in obtaining the property for 4-H,

1128
01:21:23,000 --> 01:21:28,000
the 4-H camp that's over near Salem.

1129
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:29,000
Right.

1130
01:21:29,000 --> 01:21:35,000
And I was very active in that for a long time.

1131
01:21:35,000 --> 01:21:38,000
Were you a 4-H leader as well when the children were younger?

1132
01:21:38,000 --> 01:21:40,000
Yes.

1133
01:21:40,000 --> 01:21:45,000
And I think I told you that Irma Seymour was my 4-H leader.

1134
01:21:45,000 --> 01:21:48,000
I think we talked about that.

1135
01:21:48,000 --> 01:21:55,000
So I've always been active in 4-H and still am to a certain extent.

1136
01:21:55,000 --> 01:21:58,000
We support the swimming pool at the camp.

1137
01:21:58,000 --> 01:22:01,000
I read that.

1138
01:22:01,000 --> 01:22:03,000
So interesting.

1139
01:22:03,000 --> 01:22:05,000
Were the boys in 4-H as well?

1140
01:22:05,000 --> 01:22:07,000
No, they were both eagle scouts.

1141
01:22:07,000 --> 01:22:09,000
Oh.

1142
01:22:09,000 --> 01:22:17,000
In fact, that conversation was about that because my great grandson is now in scouting.

1143
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:18,000
Wow.

1144
01:22:18,000 --> 01:22:23,000
And so I took all the scouts, always were red flannel jackets.

1145
01:22:23,000 --> 01:22:28,000
And I happened to remember that in the cupboard out there,

1146
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:35,000
I had craigs of scouting from his scouting.

1147
01:22:35,000 --> 01:22:38,000
And so I gave it to my great-grandchild.

1148
01:22:38,000 --> 01:22:44,000
And I took all the things off of it and hung it to the cleaners.

1149
01:22:44,000 --> 01:22:45,000
Oh no.

1150
01:22:45,000 --> 01:22:46,000
It's going down there.

1151
01:22:46,000 --> 01:22:47,000
That's fun.

1152
01:22:47,000 --> 01:22:48,000
Yeah.

1153
01:22:48,000 --> 01:22:49,000
That's funny.

1154
01:22:49,000 --> 01:22:50,000
Huh.

1155
01:22:50,000 --> 01:22:53,000
I think I read somewhere that Kermit was involved too with the boys scouting.

1156
01:22:53,000 --> 01:22:54,000
Yes.

1157
01:22:54,000 --> 01:23:02,000
He was with the, what, I don't know what they call that.

1158
01:23:02,000 --> 01:23:06,000
The headquarters are in Eugene for this area.

1159
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:07,000
Uh-huh.

1160
01:23:07,000 --> 01:23:11,000
And he was active in that management of that.

1161
01:23:11,000 --> 01:23:12,000
At the regional level.

1162
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:15,000
I don't know what they call them trustees or what they call them.

1163
01:23:15,000 --> 01:23:20,000
But anyway, he was active in that for quite a while.

1164
01:23:20,000 --> 01:23:23,000
That was wonderful.

1165
01:23:23,000 --> 01:23:24,000
Huh.

1166
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:31,000
So as a home economist, you think that you were more prepared than other women going into this whole

1167
01:23:31,000 --> 01:23:34,000
child-bearing thing to be able to...

1168
01:23:34,000 --> 01:23:36,000
I suppose so.

1169
01:23:36,000 --> 01:23:42,000
You know, because we learned a lot of child education and what we were supposed to do

1170
01:23:42,000 --> 01:23:46,000
and how we were supposed to handle problems and that sort of thing.

1171
01:23:46,000 --> 01:23:48,000
I think probably...

1172
01:23:48,000 --> 01:23:52,000
Did you continue to do the kind of things that you had been teaching other women to do

1173
01:23:52,000 --> 01:23:55,000
with in terms of preserving food and...

1174
01:23:55,000 --> 01:24:03,000
Well, I've always worked with the extension service to a certain extent, you know,

1175
01:24:03,000 --> 01:24:07,000
even as a volunteer.

1176
01:24:07,000 --> 01:24:08,000
And I think that I did.

1177
01:24:08,000 --> 01:24:12,000
I followed through on a lot of that.

1178
01:24:12,000 --> 01:24:13,000
Yeah.

1179
01:24:13,000 --> 01:24:15,000
Great.

1180
01:24:15,000 --> 01:24:20,000
What do you think was your strength as a mother?

1181
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:24,000
Do you think there was something that you were in the family that everybody depended on you for?

1182
01:24:25,000 --> 01:24:27,000
Cooking, I think.

1183
01:24:27,000 --> 01:24:30,000
Having a good meal.

1184
01:24:30,000 --> 01:24:36,000
Well, and I think that we cooked healthy meals because I had learned that.

1185
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:44,000
You know, we always had meat and probably potatoes of some sort or rice or starch of some sort.

1186
01:24:44,000 --> 01:24:47,000
And vegetables and salad.

1187
01:24:47,000 --> 01:24:53,000
My husband always wanted to salad because when he was in the service he didn't have any greens at all.

1188
01:24:53,000 --> 01:25:00,000
And I think we mentioned that he wanted lettuce when his brother came to visit.

1189
01:25:00,000 --> 01:25:04,000
And he always wanted greens.

1190
01:25:04,000 --> 01:25:10,000
So we always had balanced meals and we always sat down to eat together.

1191
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:20,000
And of course later my dad ate with us that's something that I would not do again because I don't think it was fair to my children.

1192
01:25:21,000 --> 01:25:27,000
When you sit down to eat your evening meal the kids want to talk about their days.

1193
01:25:27,000 --> 01:25:37,000
And my dad wanted to sort of, he was the conversationist and he wanted to tell us about his day.

1194
01:25:37,000 --> 01:25:44,000
And I don't think it was fair to my children to do that.

1195
01:25:44,000 --> 01:25:47,000
But, you know, you did what you had to do at the time.

1196
01:25:47,000 --> 01:25:50,000
They accommodated.

1197
01:25:50,000 --> 01:25:53,000
But it's true, it's not all that common out.

1198
01:25:53,000 --> 01:25:56,000
I have a regular meal that in itself is that.

1199
01:25:56,000 --> 01:26:04,000
But as a result, Kermit came home every day for lunch from the meal because he was just a short distance.

1200
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:07,000
And that was our quiet time together.

1201
01:26:07,000 --> 01:26:09,000
The two of you.

1202
01:26:09,000 --> 01:26:18,000
Because we hear and often, well, sometimes not quite often, he would bring salesman home for lunch.

1203
01:26:18,000 --> 01:26:27,000
Because the thing to do was for the salesman to take him out, you know, try to win his favor.

1204
01:26:27,000 --> 01:26:28,000
Yeah.

1205
01:26:28,000 --> 01:26:30,000
And he'd say, oh no, let's go home.

1206
01:26:30,000 --> 01:26:32,000
You know, cook or something.

1207
01:26:32,000 --> 01:26:39,000
And so, I think that that was our time together.

1208
01:26:39,000 --> 01:26:49,000
And it was also, I always had something in the pantry like a can of chicken or I could do a zillion things with chicken.

1209
01:26:49,000 --> 01:26:55,000
You know, it was chicken salad, chicken soup, chicken dumplings.

1210
01:26:55,000 --> 01:27:01,000
You know, there were lots of things I could do on the spur of the moment to...

1211
01:27:01,000 --> 01:27:06,000
And sometimes he'd just call 1130 and say, can I bring someone so home?

1212
01:27:06,000 --> 01:27:08,000
And I'd say, oh sure, you know.

1213
01:27:08,000 --> 01:27:12,000
And when you say can of chicken, was that something that you had canned?

1214
01:27:12,000 --> 01:27:14,000
No, no, it wasn't.

1215
01:27:14,000 --> 01:27:19,000
No, I didn't want anything to do with those chickens.

1216
01:27:19,000 --> 01:27:22,000
I wanted them prepared.

1217
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:28,000
Well, that's one of the luxuries we have now.

1218
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:32,000
So, tell me if you're getting tired, are you still doing all right?

1219
01:27:32,000 --> 01:27:35,000
No, I'm doing fine, but I suppose we ought to quit around three.

1220
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:40,000
All right, I'll move through this.

1221
01:27:40,000 --> 01:27:51,000
I'm almost in the same age range as your children, so I'm thinking about the era when you were raising kids and thinking about how it was such an era of change

1222
01:27:51,000 --> 01:27:54,000
and more permissiveness and that sort of thing from...

1223
01:27:54,000 --> 01:27:57,000
Yes, certainly from the era when you had been raised.

1224
